Level 73 is the 74<sup>th</sup> level of [[The Backrooms]].
==Description==
{{Blurimage|file=73.jpeg|caption=A photograph of Level 73}}
'''Level 73''', known as “Shooting Gallery” is an expansive shooting network, spanning approximately 100 km<sup>2</sup>. '''Level 73''' is primarily composed of corridors and winding hallways along with other facilities, including retail, lounges and weaponry rooms. The unusual layout of a typical shooting gallery in [[The Frontrooms]] results into multiple chambers placed intricately and improperly conceived, different gates stumbling into other shooting galleries; and rooms that are placed incorrectly. Within the compartment, shooting lanes group in a row, each lane featuring a shooting bench or table including a gun and ammunition, along with shooting targets moving forward constantly.

The flooring is more diversified and distinct in each subject matter, with most rooms having concrete, rubber, or steel flooring that is resilient, straight forward to clean, and capable of enduring the impact of expanded casings and errant bullet rounds. Steel cables column across the firing lane or bay at a suitable height corresponding to the measurement as the ceiling. The shooting targets are hung across a cable using a string, where they constantly move forward until it collides with the wanderer or the ammunition. Paintings and sculptures may be found, containing both arts and sculptures from both [[The Frontrooms]] and [[The Backrooms]].

{{Blurimage|file=Gallery.jpeg|caption=Another photograph of Level 73}}
The shooting lanes in '''Level 73''' is lit up by bright and adjustable fluorescent lighting fixtures, guaranteeing no darkness in the surrounding region. The ceiling contains a small ventilation system, small remote holes from the bullets, or occasionally ceiling windows; portraying as a light source for the shooting range. The backstop at the end of each shooting lane wall is a crucial protection attribute, preventing gunfire from departing the specified firing area.

Certain shooting galleries might possess a room or lounge that functions as a separate room from its own, such as a waiting area or retail and rental services where a wide range of weapons, ammunition, and accessories can be purchased or found, by [[Entity 9|facelings]] operating the store.

Weapons include pistols, rifles, shotguns, and air guns; where one may locate these commodities in other locations, like floors or shooting lanes. Crossbows, archery, knives, and other throwing weapons are also available as additional weapons. However, some weapons may be damaged or malfunction, thus making them nearly-worthless. Aside from weapons, other items can be found, including papers, loose planks, and empty cardboard boxes. Essential items are also found such as [[Object 1|Almond Water]], royal rations, tools and supply drops. Vending machines are found in this level, containing a decent amount of packaged food, which makes it a reliable source of food in Level 73. Windows may also be found, which are harmless (when not touched) and useful; essential for guiding one in The Flickering Aftershocks.

It is widely acknowledged that the shooting gallery is considered to be unnatural and unsettling. Many rooms include unsuitable width/length measurements, unnecessary heights, and pointless pillars obstructing the shooting target. Furthermore, a chamber might be barred, with few things inside that cannot confirm to any use, or it might exist in an abandoned condition with everything being messy and demolished.
==Hazards==
{{Blurimage|file=67.jpeg|caption=A photograph of an abandoned shooting range in Level 73}}
Level 73’s environment is relatively unsafe, as the main hazard is the shooting targets that constantly move forward, pushing one if they get too close, leading to bruises, broken bones and other injuries, depending on the type and speed of the shooting target. When shooting targets are shot down, they will malfunction and fall down, though the amount of shots required to take down a target varies by the material it is made out of. Additionally, the shooting target will have other properties, such as the size, height and speed of the target.  Usually the size and material of shooting targets in Level 73 is 18.5 in. x 18.5 and made of paper or steel but sometimes warp and may be other materials (titanium, gold, even uranium) or sizes.

Other hazards such as nails poking through the floor, sharp pieces of metal being present, slippery surfaces or The Blackout phenomenon. Level 73’s non-environmental hazards pose a risk to anyone wandering inside, such as getting splinters from the broken metal, contracting tetanus from the exposed nails, unintentionally slipping through the floor or unable to sightread the moving shooting targets. Those hazards, combined with the addition of The Flickering Aftershocks and the shooting targets, makes Level 73 a somewhat dangerous level.

==Entities==
The only entities found in this level are [[Entity 9|Facelings]].
==Colonies and Outposts==
===The Gunners===
A group of thirteen survivors have made this enclave their home. Interestingly, The Gunners are admirable and willing to trade with other explorers. They have an armory of weapons and are accommodating to exchange firearms for food, precious almond water, and rare and prized resources in the Backrooms.

==Entrances and Exits==
===Entrances===
* Three-story abandoned cyan building randomly manifest through the whole of [[Level 11]], entering these buildings will lead here.
* Passing out, most commonly from drunkenness in [[Level 72]] may result in one waking up here.
* Noclipping through an arcade machine named "Malla Halla" in [[Level 25]] is guaranteed to bring an individual here.
* Why shoot targets when you can have some [[Level Fun|fun]]? {{User:ItzLambda/fun}}
* Rare blue doors found in occasionally lead to commercial sectors of [[Level 146]].
===Exits===
* Exiting through the fire emergency doors will lead one to [[Level 74]].
* A bench in '''Level 73''' possesses a chance of noclipping through it due to the unstable material used, which will lead one to [[Level 39]].
* Coating a bullet in [[Object_12|Liquid Pain]] or any other acidic substance sends wanderers to [[Level 597]].
* Corridor has an erratic probability of fading into [[Level 74]] or [[Level 76]].
* Shooting an indestructible golden bowling pin will lead one to [[Level 499]]; albeit the bowling pin is extremely rare for one to come across.
* Repeatedly punching a target, composed of steel may lead to [[Level 464]], although the chances are low.

